  "answer": {
    "role": "assistant",
    "content": "<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n  <meta charset=\"utf-8\">\n  <title>P vs NP — Interactive Demonstration</title>\n  <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width,initial-scale=1\">\n  <style>\n    body { font-family: system-ui, -apple-system, \"Segoe UI\", Roboto, \"Helvetica Neue\", Arial; margin: 18px; color:#111; line-height:1.45; }\n    h1 { margin-bottom: 6px; }\n    p.lead { margin-top:6px; color:#333; }\n    section { border:1px solid #ddd; padding:12px; margin:12px 0; border-radius:8px; background:#fafafa; }\n    label { display:inline-block; margin:6px 0; }\n    input[type=\"number\"], select, textarea { font-family:inherit; font-size:13px; padding:6px; margin-left:6px; }\n    button { margin:6px 6px 0 0; padding:8px 12px; }\n    .small { font-size:13px; color:#555; }\n    .controls { display:flex; gap:10px; flex-wrap:wrap; align-items:center; }\n    .row { margin:8px 0; }\n    pre { background:#fff; border:1px solid #eee; padding:8px; overflow:auto; max-height:200px; }\n    .progress { height:14px; background:#eee; border-radius:8px; overflow:hidden; width:100%; margin-top:6px; }\n    .bar { height:100%; background:linear-gradient(90deg,#6fa8dc,#3b82f6); width:0%; transition:width 120ms; }\n    .result { padding:8px; margin-top:8px; border-radius:6px; background:#fff; border:1px solid #eee; }\n    .grid { display:grid; grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr; gap:12px; }\n    @media (max-width:700px) { .grid { grid-template-columns:1fr; } }\n    code { background:#f7f7f7; padding:2px 4px; border-radius:3px; }\n    .ok { color:green; font-weight:600; }\n    .bad { color:#b33; font-weight:600; }\n  </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n  <h1>P vs NP — Interactive Demonstration</h1>\n  <p class=\"lead\">This single-page interactive demo illustrates the difference between \"P\" (problems solvable in polynomial time) and \"NP\" (problems whose solutions can be verified in polynomial time). It does not resolve the open question \"P vs NP\" — that remains one of the major open problems in theoretical computer science. Use the controls below to experiment with small examples.</p>\n\n  <section>\n    <h2>Quick definitions</h2>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Decision problem</strong>: answer is YES/NO (e.g., \"Does this Boolean formula have a satisfying assignment?\").</li>\n      <li><strong>P</strong>: class of decision problems solvable by a deterministic algorithm in polynomial time (w.r.t. input size).</li>\n      <li><strong>NP</strong>: class of decision problems where, if the answer is YES, there exists a short certificate (witness) that a polynomial-time algorithm can verify.</li>\n      <li><strong>NP-complete</strong>: problems in NP that are at least as hard as every other problem in NP; if any NP-complete problem is in P, then P = NP.</li>\n    </ul>\n  </section>\n\n  <section id=\"sat-demo\">\n    <h2>SAT (Satisfiability) example — verify vs search</h2>\n    <p class=\"small\">SAT is the canonical NP-complete problem: given a Boolean formula in CNF, does there exist an assignment of true/false to variables that makes the formula true? If someone hands you an assignment (a certificate), you can verify it quickly. Finding that assignment (without extra information) appears hard in general: known algorithms are exponential in the worst case.</p>\n\n    <div class=\"grid\">\n      <div>\n        <label>Number of variables: <input id=\"sat-n\" type=\"number\" min=\"1\" max=\"24\" value=\"6\"></label>\n        <label>Clauses: <input id=\"sat-m\" type=\"number\" min=\"1\" max=\"50\" value=\"8\"></label>\n        <div class=\"row controls\">\n          <button id=\"generate-sat\">Generate random 3-CNF</button>\n          <button id=\"show-example\">Load small example</button>\n        </div>\n\n        <div class=\"row\">\n          <label>Estimated ops/sec (for time estimate): <input id=\"ops-per-sec\" type=\"number\" min=\"1000\" step=\"1000\" value=\"10000000\"></label>\n        </div>\n\n        <div class=\"row\">\n          <label>Formula (CNF, each clause on its own line, variables like x1, x2; use - for negation):</label>\n          <textarea id=\"cnf\" rows=\"8\" style=\"width:100%; font-family:monospace;\"></textarea>\n        </div>\n\n        <div class=\"row\">\n          <button id=\"verify-assignment\">Verify assignment</button>\n          <button id=\"bruteforce-solve\">Brute-force search</button>\n          <button id=\"dpll-solve\">Backtracking (pruning) search</button>\n        </div>\n\n        <div class=\"row\">\n          <label>Assignment to verify (e.g. x1=1,x2=0,...): <input id=\"assignment\" style=\"width:50%\"></label>\n        </div>\n\n        <div class=\"row\">\n          <div class=\"progress\"><div id=\"sat-progress\" class=\"bar\"></div></div>\n          <div id=\"sat-output\" class=\"result\"></div>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div>\n        <h3>Notes & tips</h3>\n        <ul>\n          <li>Verifier: given an assignment, checking every clause is linear in the formula size (fast).</li>\n          <li>Brute-force: tries all 2^n assignments. Time doubles when you add one variable — exponential growth.</li>\n          <li>Backtracking: assigns variables and prunes partial assignments when a clause becomes impossible; often much faster than naive brute force for structured formulas.</li>\n        </ul>\n\n        <h3>Small example</h3>\n        <pre id=\"example-text\">x1 or x2 or x3\n-x1 or x2 or x4\n-x2 or -x3 or x4\nx3 or -x4 or x5\n-x1 or -x5 or x6</pre>\n\n        <h3>Explanation</h3>\n        <p class=\"small\">Try increasing variables and see how brute-force time grows (estimation shown). The backtracking solver may quickly find a solution or prove unsatisfiable for many instances — but worst-case behavior still grows exponentially for general SAT.</p>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </section>\n\n  <section>\n    <h2>Subset Sum (certificate vs search)</h2>\n    <p class=\"small\">Given a list of integers and a target T, does a subset sum to exactly T? If someone gives you the subset (certificate), verifying is fast. Searching can be exponential (2^n). There's a dynamic programming algorithm that's pseudo-polynomial (O(n * T)).</p>\n\n    <div class=\"row controls\">\n      <label>n: <input id=\"sub-n\" type=\"number\" min=\"1\" max=\"24\" value=\"10\"></label>\n      <button id=\"gen-sub\">Generate numbers</button>\n      <button id=\"solve-sub-brute\">Brute-force</button>\n      <button id=\"solve-sub-dp\">Dynamic Programming (pseudo-polynomial)</button>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"row\">\n      <label>Numbers (comma separated): <input id=\"sub-arr\" style=\"width:70%\"></label>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"row\">\n      <label>Target T: <input id=\"sub-target\" type=\"number\" value=\"15\"></label>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"row\">\n      <div class=\"progress\"><div id=\"sub-progress\" class=\"bar\"></div></div>\n      <div id=\"sub-output\" class=\"result\"></div>\n    </div>\n  </section>\n\n  <section>\n    <h2>Polynomial-time example: BFS shortest path (in unweighted graph)</h2>\n    <p class=\"small\">Find shortest path in an unweighted graph using BFS — this runs in O(V + E) time (polynomial). Use this to contrast with exponential SAT/SubsetSum searches.</p>\n\n    <div class=\"row controls\">\n      <label>Nodes: <input id=\"g-n\" type=\"number\" min=\"2\" max=\"200\" value=\"20\"></label>\n      <label>Edge probability (0..1): <input id=\"g-p\" type=\"number\" min=\"0\" max=\"1\" step=\"0.01\" value=\"0.12\"></label>\n      <button id=\"gen-graph\">Generate graph</button>\n      <button id=\"run-bfs\">Run BFS (shortest path)</button>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"row\">\n      <div id=\"graph-output\" class=\"result small\"></div>\n    </div>\n  </section>\n\n  <section>\n    <h2>Key takeaway</h2>\n    <p>P vs NP asks: is every problem whose solutions can be verified quickly (in polynomial time) also solvable quickly? Most researchers believe P != NP, but the question remains unproven. If someone produced a polynomial-time algorithm for any NP-complete problem, it would imply P = NP, with huge consequences — both positive (faster algorithms) and potentially negative (cryptography broken).</p>\n  </section>\n\n  <script>\n    // --- Helpers ---\n    function parseCNF(text) {\n      // Each line: literals separated by spaces or ors. Literals like x1 or -x1\n      const lines = text.split(/\\r?\\n/).map(s => s.trim()).filter(Boolean);\n      const clauses = [];\n      let maxvar = 0;\n      for (const l of lines) {\n        // split by spaces or \"or\"\n        const tokens = l.split(/\\s+|or/i).map(t => t.trim()).filter(Boolean);\n        const clause = [];\n        for (const t of tokens) {\n          const m = t.match(/^(-)?x(\\d+)$/i);\n          if (!m) continue;\n          const neg = !!m[1];\n          const v = parseInt(m[2], 10);\n          maxvar = Math.max(maxvar, v);\n          clause.push({v: v-1, neg});\n        }\n        if (clause.length) clauses.push(clause);\n      }\n      return {clauses, maxvar};\n    }\n\n    function evalClause(clause, assignment) {\n      // clause: array of {v,neg}; assignment: array of 0/1 or undefined\n      for (const lit of clause) {\n        const val = assignment[lit.v];\n        if (val === undefined) {\n          // unknown: cannot confirm true, but clause might be satisfied later\n          if (!lit.neg) {\n            // can't say true\n          }\n        }\n        if (val !== undefined) {\n          const litVal = lit.neg ? !val : !!val;\n          if (litVal) return true;\n        }\n      }\n      // Not satisfied by known assignments. If any literal has undefined, clause is not yet falsified.\n      const anyUnknown = clause.some(l => assignment[l.v] === undefined);\n      return anyUnknown ? null : false; // true / null (unknown) / false (falsified)\n    }\n\n    // Verifier: check full assignment\n    function verifyAssignmentCNF(clauses, assign) {\n      for (const c of clauses) {\n        let sat = false;\n        for (const lit of c) {\n          const v = assign[lit.v];\n          if (v === undefined) return {ok:false, reason:\"assignment is incomplete\"};\n          if (lit.neg ? !v : v) { sat = true; break; }\n        }\n        if (!sat) return {ok:false, reason:\"clause unsatisfied\"};\n      }\n      return {ok:true};\n    }\n\n    // Brute-force SAT with chunked iteration to keep UI responsive\n    function bruteForceSolve(clauses, n, onProgress, onFound, onDone, cancelToken) {\n      const total = 1 << n;\n      let i = 0;\n      const chunk = 8192; // assignments per chunk\n      const start = performance.now();\n      function step() {\n        if (cancelToken.cancelled) { onDone({cancelled:true}); return; }\n        const limit = Math.min(i + chunk, total);\n        for (; i < limit; i++) {\n          // build assignment bitwise\n          const assign = new Array(n);\n          for (let b=0;b<n;b++) assign[b] = !!(i & (1<<b));\n          // check\n          let ok = true;\n          for (const c of clauses) {\n            let sat = false;\n            for (const lit of c) {\n              const val = assign[lit.v];\n              if ((lit.neg && !val) || (!lit.neg && val)) { sat = true; break; }\n            }\n            if (!sat) { ok = false; break; }\n          }\n          if (ok) {\n            onFound({assignment: assign, tried: i+1, elapsed: performance.now()-start});\n            return;\n          }\n        }\n        onProgress({tried:i, total, elapsed: performance.now()-start});\n        if (i < total) {\n          // schedule next chunk\n          setTimeout(step, 0);\n        } else {\n          onDone({found:false, tried:total, elapsed: performance.now()-start});\n        }\n      }\n      setTimeout(step, 20);\n    }\n\n    // Backtracking with early pruning (simple DPLL-like)\n    function dpllSolve(clauses, n, onProgress, onFound, onDone, cancelToken) {\n      const start = performance.now();\n      const assignment = new Array(n);\n      let steps = 0;\n      let lastProgressTime = performance.now();\n\n      function unitPropagate(clauses, assignment) {\n        let changed = true;\n        while (changed) {\n          changed = false;\n          for (const c of clauses) {\n            let cntUnk = 0; let lastLit = null; let satisfied = false;\n            for (const lit of c) {\n              const val = assignment[lit.v];\n              if (val === undefined) { cntUnk++; lastLit = lit; }\n              else {\n                if ((lit.neg && !val) || (!lit.neg && val)) { satisfied = true; break; }\n              }\n            }\n            if (satisfied) continue;\n            if (cntUnk === 0) return false; // clause falsified\n            if (cntUnk === 1) {\n              // must assign lastLit to satisfy clause\n              const lit = lastLit;\n              assignment[lit.v] = lit.neg ? 0 : 1;\n              changed = true;\n            }\n          }\n        }\n        return true;\n      }\n\n      function recurse(idx) {\n        if (cancelToken.cancelled) return false;\n        if (idx === n) {\n          // verify full\n          for (const c of clauses) {\n            let sat = false;\n            for (const lit of c) {\n              const v = assignment[lit.v];\n              if ((lit.neg && !v) || (!lit.neg && v)) { sat = true; break; }\n            }\n            if (!sat) return false;\n          }\n          onFound({assignment: assignment.slice(), tried: steps, elapsed: performance.now()-start});\n          return true;\n        }\n        // try undefined variable: but use unit propagation first\n        // make copy of assignment to try both values\n        const t = assignment[idx];\n        if (t !== undefined) return recurse(idx+1);\n\n        for (const val of [0,1]) {\n          steps++;\n          assignment[idx] = val;\n          const saved = assignment.slice();\n          const ok = unitPropagate(clauses, assignment);\n          if (ok) {\n            const now = performance.now();\n            if (now - lastProgressTime > 120) {\n              onProgress({tried: steps, elapsed: now-start});\n              lastProgressTime = now;\n            }\n            // find next index\n            let next = idx+1;\n            while (next < n && assignment[next] !== undefined) next++;\n            if (recurse(next)) return true;\n          }\n          // backtrack\n          for (let i=0;i<n;i++) assignment[i] = saved[i];\n        }\n        assignment[idx] = undefined;\n        return false;\n      }\n\n      // initial unit propagation\n      const ok0 = unitPropagate(clauses, assignment);\n      if (!ok0) { onDone({found:false, tried:0, elapsed: performance.now()-start}); return; }\n      const next0 = assignment.findIndex(v=>v===undefined);\n      if (next0 === -1) {\n        // fully assigned\n        onFound({assignment: assignment.slice(), tried:0, elapsed: performance.now()-start});\n        return;\n      }\n      setTimeout(() => {\n        const found = recurse(next0);\n        if (!found && !cancelToken.cancelled) onDone({found:false, tried:steps, elapsed: performance.now()-start});\n      }, 20);\n    }\n\n    // Subset sum brute-force\n    function subsetBrute(arr, T, onProgress, onFound, onDone, cancelToken) {\n      const n = arr.length;\n      const total = 1 << n;\n      let i=0; const chunk=8192; const start=performance.now();\n      function step() {\n        if (cancelToken.cancelled) { onDone({cancelled:true}); return; }\n        const limit = Math.min(total, i+chunk);\n        for (; i<limit; i++) {\n          let s=0;\n          for (let b=0;b<n;b++) if (i&(1<<b)) s+=arr[b];\n          if (s===T) {\n            const chosen=[];\n            for (let b=0;b<n;b++) if (i&(1<<b)) chosen.push(arr[b]);\n            onFound({subset:chosen, tried:i+1, elapsed: performance.now()-start});\n            return;\n          }\n        }\n        onProgress({tried:i,total,elapsed:performance.now()-start});\n        if (i<total) setTimeout(step,0);\n        else onDone({found:false,tried:total,elapsed:performance.now()-start});\n      }\n      setTimeout(step,20);\n    }\n\n    // Subset sum DP (pseudo-polynomial)\n    function subsetDP(arr, T) {\n      const n = arr.length;\n      const reachable = new Array(T+1).fill(false);\n      reachable[0]=true;\n      const parent = new Array(T+1).fill(-1); // store last index used\n      const from = new Array(T+1).fill(-1);\n      for (let i=0;i<n;i++) {\n        const v=arr[i];\n        for (let s=T;s>=v;s--) {\n          if (!reachable[s] && reachable[s-v]) { reachable[s]=true; parent[s]=i; from[s]=s-v; }\n        }\n      }\n      if (!reachable[T]) return {found:false};\n      const subset=[];\n      let s=T;\n      while (s>0) {\n        const idx=parent[s];\n        subset.push(arr[idx]);\n        s=from[s];\n      }\n      return {found:true, subset};\n    }\n\n    // BFS\n    function genGraph(n,p) {\n      const edges = Array.from({length:n}, ()=>[]);\n      for (let i=0;i<n;i++) for (let j=i+1;j<n;j++) if (Math.random()<p) {\n        edges[i].push(j); edges[j].push(i);\n      }\n      return edges;\n    }\n    function bfs(edges, start, goal) {\n      const n = edges.length;\n      const q=[start];\n      const prev = new Array(n).fill(-1);\n      prev[start]=-2;\n      for (let i=0;i<q.length;i++) {\n        const u=q[i];\n        if (u===goal) break;\n        for (const v of edges[u]) {\n          if (prev[v]===-1) { prev[v]=u; q.push(v); }\n        }\n      }\n      if (prev[goal]===-1) return null;\n      const path=[];\n      let cur=goal;\n      while (cur!=-2) { path.push(cur); cur=prev[cur]; }\n      path.reverse();\n      return path;\n    }\n\n    // --- UI wiring ---\n    const cnfTA = document.getElementById('cnf');\n    const satN = document.getElementById('sat-n');\n    const satM = document.getElementById('sat-m');\n    const exampleText = document.getElementById('example-text');\n    document.getElementById('show-example').onclick = ()=> { cnfTA.value = exampleText.textContent.trim(); };\n\n    document.getElementById('generate-sat').onclick = ()=> {\n      const n = Math.max(1, Math.min(24, parseInt(satN.value)||6));\n      const m = Math.max(1, Math.min(50, parseInt(satM.value)||8));\n      // generate 3-CNF: each clause with up to 3 distinct literals\n      const lines = [];\n      for (let i=0;i<m;i++) {\n        const k = 3;\n        const used = new Set();\n        const lits = [];\n        while (lits.length<k) {\n          const v = Math.floor(Math.random()*n)+1;\n          if (used.has(v)) continue;\n          used.add(v);\n          const neg = Math.random()<0.5 ? '-' : '';\n          lits.push(neg + 'x' + v);\n        }\n        lines.push(lits.join(' or '));\n      }\n      cnfTA.value = lines.join('\\n');\n    };\n\n    const satOutput = document.getElementById('sat-output');\n    const satProgressBar = document.getElementById('sat-progress');\n    let satCancel = {cancelled:false};\n\n    document.getElementById('verify-assignment').onclick = ()=> {\n      const p = parseCNF(cnfTA.value);\n      if (p.clauses.length===0) { satOutput.innerHTML = '<span class=\"bad\">No clauses found in formula.</span>'; return; }\n      const assignText = document.getElementById('assignment').value;\n      const assign = new Array(p.maxvar).fill(undefined);\n      const m = assignText.split(',').map(s=>s.trim()).filter(Boolean);\n      for (const t of m) {\n        const mm = t.match(/^x(\\d+)\\s*=\\s*([01])$/i);\n        if (!mm) continue;\n        const v = parseInt(mm[1],10)-1;\n        const val = mm[2]==='1'?1:0;\n        assign[v]=val;\n      }\n      const res = verifyAssignmentCNF(p.clauses, assign);\n      if (res.ok) satOutput.innerHTML = '<span class=\"ok\">Assignment satisfies formula. Verified quickly (linear time).</span>';\n      else satOutput.innerHTML = '<span class=\"bad\">Not a satisfying assignment: '+res.reason+'</span>';\n    };\n\n    document.getElementById('bruteforce-solve').onclick = ()=> {\n      satCancel.cancelled = true;\n      satCancel = {cancelled:false};\n      satProgressBar.style.width='0%';\n      const p = parseCNF(cnfTA.value);\n      const n = Math.max(p.maxvar, 0);\n      if (p.clauses.length===0) { satOutput.innerHTML = '<span class=\"bad\">No clauses found.</span>'; return; }\n      if (n>24) { satOutput.innerHTML = '<span class=\"bad\">Too many variables for brute-force demo (max 24).</span>'; return; }\n      const total = 1<<n;\n      const opsPerSec = Math.max(1000, parseInt(document.getElementById('ops-per-sec').value)||10000000);\n      satOutput.innerHTML = 'Starting brute-force (2^'+n+' = '+total+' assignments). Est. time at '+opsPerSec+' ops/sec: '+(Math.round((total/opsPerSec)*100)/100)+'s';\n      const start = performance.now();\n      bruteForceSolve(p.clauses, n,\n        ({tried,total,elapsed})=>{\n          const pct = Math.min(100, Math.round((tried/total)*10000)/100);\n          satProgressBar.style.width = pct+'%';\n          satOutput.innerHTML = 'Tried '+tried+' / '+total+' assignments. Elapsed: '+(elapsed/1000).toFixed(2)+'s';\n        },\n        ({assignment,tried,elapsed})=>{\n          satProgressBar.style.width = '100%';\n          satOutput.innerHTML = '<span class=\"ok\">Satisfying assignment found in '+(elapsed/1000).toFixed(3)+'s after trying '+tried+' assignments:</span><br><pre>'+assignment.map((v,i) => 'x'+(i+1)+'='+ (v?1:0)).join(', ')+'</pre>';\n        },\n        ({found,tried,elapsed,cancelled})=>{\n          if (cancelled) { satOutput.innerHTML = '<span class=\"small\">Cancelled.</span>'; satProgressBar.style.width='0%'; return; }\n          if (!found) {\n            satProgressBar.style.width = '100%';\n            satOutput.innerHTML = '<span class=\"bad\">No satisfying assignment (exhaustive). Tried '+tried+' assignments in '+(elapsed/1000).toFixed(3)+'s.</span>';\n          }\n        },\n        satCancel\n      );\n    };\n\n    document.getElementById('dpll-solve').onclick = ()=> {\n      satCancel.cancelled = true;\n      satCancel = {cancelled:false};\n      satProgressBar.style.width='0%';\n      const p = parseCNF(cnfTA.value);\n      if (p.clauses.length===0) { satOutput.innerHTML = '<span class=\"bad\">No clauses found.</span>'; return; }\n      satOutput.innerHTML = 'Starting backtracking search (with basic unit propagation)...';\n      dpllSolve(p.clauses, Math.max(p.maxvar,0),\n        ({tried,elapsed})=>{\n          satProgressBar.style.width = Math.min(100, Math.round(Math.sqrt(tried)%100)) + '%'; // approximate visual\n          satOutput.innerHTML = 'Steps: '+tried+' Elapsed: '+(elapsed/1000).toFixed(3)+'s';\n        },\n        ({assignment,tried,elapsed})=>{\n          satProgressBar.style.width = '100%';\n          satOutput.innerHTML = '<span class=\"ok\">Solution found in '+(elapsed/1000).toFixed(3)+'s (steps ~'+tried+'):</span><br><pre>'+assignment.map((v,i) => 'x'+(i+1)+'='+ (v?1:0)).join(', ')+'</pre>';\n        },\n        ({found,tried,elapsed})=>{\n          if (!found) {\n            satProgressBar.style.width = '100%';\n            satOutput.innerHTML = '<span class=\"bad\">Proved UNSAT after steps ~'+tried+' (elapsed '+(elapsed/1000).toFixed(3)+'s).</span>';\n          }\n        },\n        satCancel\n      );\n    };\n\n    // Subset sum UI\n    const subArrIn = document.getElementById('sub-arr');\n    const subOut = document.getElementById('sub-output');\n    const subProgress = document.getElementById('sub-progress');\n    document.getElementById('gen-sub').onclick = ()=> {\n      const n = Math.max(1, Math.min(22, parseInt(document.getElementById('sub-n').value)||10));\n      const arr = Array.from({length:n}, ()=>Math.floor(Math.random()*20)+1);\n      subArrIn.value = arr.join(', ');\n      document.getElementById('sub-target').value = Math.floor(arr.reduce((a,b)=>a+b,0)/2);\n    };\n    let subCancel = {cancelled:false};\n    document.getElementById('solve-sub-brute').onclick = ()=> {\n      subCancel.cancelled = true; subCancel={cancelled:false};\n      subProgress.style.width='0%';\n      const arr = subArrIn.value.split(',').map(s=>parseInt(s,10)).filter(x=>!isNaN(x));\n      const T = parseInt(document.getElementById('sub-target').value)||0;\n      if (arr.length===0) { subOut.innerHTML='<span class=\"bad\">No numbers provided.</span>'; return; }\n      if (arr.length>24) { subOut.innerHTML='<span class=\"bad\">Too many numbers for brute-force demo (max 24).</span>'; return; }\n      subOut.innerHTML = 'Brute-force searching (2^'+arr.length+' subsets)...';\n      subsetBrute(arr,T,\n        ({tried,total,elapsed})=>{\n          subProgress.style.width = Math.min(100, Math.round((tried/total)*10000)/100)+'%';\n          subOut.innerHTML = 'Tried '+tried+' / '+total+' subsets. Elapsed: '+(elapsed/1000).toFixed(2)+'s';\n        },\n        ({subset,tried,elapsed})=>{\n          subProgress.style.width='100%';\n          subOut.innerHTML = '<span class=\"ok\">Subset found in '+(elapsed/1000).toFixed(3)+'s after '+tried+' checks:</span><br><pre>'+subset.join(', ')+'</pre>';\n        },\n        ({found,tried,elapsed,cancelled})=>{\n          if (cancelled) { subOut.innerHTML='<span class=\"small\">Cancelled.</span>'; subProgress.style.width='0%'; return; }\n          if (!found) { subProgress.style.width='100%'; subOut.innerHTML='<span class=\"bad\">No subset sums to target. Tried '+tried+' subsets in '+(elapsed/1000).toFixed(3)+'s.</span>'; }\n        },\n        subCancel\n      );\n    };\n\n    document.getElementById('solve-sub-dp').onclick = ()=> {\n      const arr = subArrIn.value.split(',').map(s=>parseInt(s,10)).filter(x=>!isNaN(x));\n      const T = parseInt(document.getElementById('sub-target').value)||0;\n      if (arr.length===0) { subOut.innerHTML='<span class=\"bad\">No numbers provided.</span>'; return; }\n      const start = performance.now();\n      const res = subsetDP(arr,T);\n      const elapsed = performance.now()-start;\n      if (res.found) {\n        subProgress.style.width='100%';\n        subOut.innerHTML = '<span class=\"ok\">DP found subset in '+(elapsed/1000).toFixed(4)+'s (pseudo-polynomial time O(n*T)):</span><br><pre>'+res.subset.join(', ')+'</pre>';\n      } else {\n        subProgress.style.width='100%';\n        subOut.innerHTML = '<span class=\"bad\">No subset sums to target (DP). Elapsed: '+(elapsed/1000).toFixed(4)+'s.</span>';\n      }\n    };\n\n    // BFS UI\n    let currentGraph = null;\n    document.getElementById('gen-graph').onclick = ()=> {\n      const n = Math.max(2, Math.min(200, parseInt(document.getElementById('g-n').value)||20));\n      const p = Math.max(0, Math.min(1, parseFloat(document.getElementById('g-p').value)||0.12));\n      currentGraph = genGraph(n,p);\n      document.getElementById('graph-output').textContent = 'Generated graph: '+n+' nodes. Average degree ≈ '+(currentGraph.reduce((a,b)=>a+b.length,0)/n).toFixed(2)+'.';\n    };\n    document.getElementById('run-bfs').onclick = ()=> {\n      if (!currentGraph) { document.getElementById('graph-output').textContent = 'Generate a graph first.'; return; }\n      const n = currentGraph.length;\n      const s = 0, g = n-1;\n      const start = performance.now();\n      const path = bfs(currentGraph, s, g);\n      const elapsed = performance.now()-start;\n      if (path) {\n        document.getElementById('graph-output').innerHTML = '<span class=\"ok\">Path found (BFS, O(V+E)) in '+(elapsed).toFixed(3)+'ms. Length: '+(path.length-1)+' hops. Path: '+path.join(' → ')+'</span>';\n      } else {\n        document.getElementById('graph-output').innerHTML = '<span class=\"bad\">No path from 0 to '+(n-1)+'. BFS finished in '+(elapsed).toFixed(3)+'ms.</span>';\n      }\n    };\n\n    // initial content\n    document.getElementById('show-example').click();\n    document.getElementById('gen-graph').click();\n\n    // Cancel any running searches when window is hidden or beforeunload\n    window.addEventListener('visibilitychange', ()=> { if (document.hidden) { satCancel.cancelled=true; subCancel.cancelled=true; }});\n    window.addEventListener('beforeunload', ()=> { satCancel.cancelled=true; subCancel.cancelled=true; });\n  </script>\n</body>\n</html>"
